Over the last two decades, the Learning Sciences has pushed for deep understandings of learning that can support the design of settings and tools, as well as the types of interactions and disciplinary thinking that might ideally emerge within those settings (Sawyer, 2005). Further, learning scientists concerned with equity have developed strands of research that treat learning as a fundamentally cultural process situated within wider social, political and economic constraints on learning for youth and communities (Gutierrez, 2008; Nasir, et. al., 2006; Lee, 2012; Medin &amp; Bang, 2014). Grounded in this intellectual history, this capacity building project organized two convenings of junior and senior scholars of learning in order to: 1) collectively identify and name the ways explicit engagement with culture, power relations and ethics is necessary for rigorous, equity-oriented research; 2) clearly articulate how these perspectives substantively influence both the design of new technologies and the design and study of learning environments; 3) strategize about how to further establish these conceptual tools within Cyberlearning, and the Learning Sciences more broadly and 4) map a research agenda that informs the theorization, design and study of new technological genres and learning arrangements. These convenings determined that political and ethical perspectives on the study of culture, learning and technology constitute a paradigm shift that is necessary for the Learning Sciences to address the needs of all students and communities.

This project has worked to delineate the specific areas that necessitate new forms of research and articulate criteria that can be used to further advance the rigor and imperative of equity-oriented research in the Learning Sciences. Our deliverables are: 




Conceptual: new articulations of relationships between learning theory and critical theories; delineations of political perspectives on learning, and the need to couple analyses of power with ethical perspectives (what kinds of ethical relations and forms of educational activity we are working to build); 


Methodological: participatory and community based design research methodologies;  


Pedagogical: developing robust tools and designs for formal and informal educational environments, developing and institutionalizing spaces to mentor the next generation of scholars;


Professional: a network of junior and mid-level scholars poised to intervene and take leadership roles in the field. 



More specifically, these outcomes have taken the shape of publications such as Power and Privilege in the Learning Sciences (Esmonde &amp; Booker, 2016); The Learning Sciences in a New Era of U.S. Nationalism (The Politics of Learning Writing Collective, 2017); and the organization of a special issue of Cognition &amp; Instruction focused on the theme "STEM Learning Towards What Ends?" (McKinney de Royston &amp; Sengupta Irving, in development). Our work has also resulted in the establishment of an inter-generational "virtual lab" that brings together 11 faculty and 30 graduate students from across the country working to deepen and advance socio-cultural, political and ethical perspectives on learning. This cross-institutional lab is refining and implementing the research agenda crafted through the convenings organized through this project. Lastly, the PI?s for this project and a participant were invited to speak at the closing presidential session of ICLS (International Conference of the Learning Sciences) 2018 in London. The focus of the forum was on how we can make learning sciences research "count" more broadly, with an emphasis on political and cultural perspectives. 



